@article{mckee_uniqueness_2007,
	title = {On the {Uniqueness} of {Attentional} {Capture} by {Uninformative} {Gaze} {Cues}: {Facilitation} {Interacts} {With} the {Simon} {Effect} and is {Rarely} {Followed} by {IOR}},
	volume = {61},
	copyright = {Copyright Canadian Psychological Association Dec 2007},
	issn = {11961961},
	shorttitle = {On the {Uniqueness} of {Attentional} {Capture} by {Uninformative} {Gaze} {Cues}},
	url = {http://www.proquest.com/docview/200364487/abstract/C89E8F5054F472EPQ/1},
	abstract = {Orienting to an uninformative peripheral cue is characterized by a brief facilitation followed by a long-lasting inhibition once attention is removed from the cued location. Although central gaze cues cause reflexive orienting, the inhibitory effect that is relatively ubiquitous following exogenous orienting to uninformative peripheral cues has been relatively rare. We hypothesized that IOR might be seen following gaze-induced orienting if attention were effectively returned to centre by a return gaze or return flash. The time-course of gaze-directed orienting was measured by varying the interval between the gaze cue and a peripheral target requiring an orientation discrimination (permitting measurement of the Simon effect). Significant facilitation was observed at all but the longest SOA tested, 2,880 ms, by which time the facilitation had disappeared with no evidence of IOR. Gaze-induced cuing (which was unaffected by return cue condition) interacted with the Simon effect, decreasing it at the gazed-at location, a pattern that is not seen with more typical endogenous and exogenous cuing. [PUBLICATION ABSTRACT]},
	language = {English},
	number = {4},
	urldate = {2021-09-22},
	journal = {Canadian Journal of Experimental Psychology},
	author = {McKee, Darren and Christie, John and Klein, Raymond},
	month = dec,
	year = {2007},
	note = {Num Pages: 11
Place: Ottawa, Canada
Publisher: Canadian Psychological Association},
	keywords = {Cognition \& reasoning, Medical imaging, Preschool children, Psychology, Studies, notion},
	pages = {293--303},
	annote = {***STUDY QUESTION***
*************************
STUDY SUMMARY
*************************
Study Question:Can we produce IOR in gaze-cuing?
Study Result: No.
Hypothesis: If attention is oriented back to fixation following an uninformative gaze cue, then IOR will be observed.
Procedure Summary: Past research in gaze-cueing has shown that you cannot produce IOR with gaze-cuing. Posner \& Cohen (1984) showed that if attention remains at the cued location, you do not get an IOR effect. So, this study hypothesized that if gaze-cuing is such that people keep their attention oriented to the cued location, then cuing attention back to fixation should produce an IOR effect for the area originally cued.
There were two experiments: 1a and 1b.
1a used SOAs of 180, 360, 720, and 1440ms. Participants in 1a did the experiment individually, each in separate rooms.
1b used SOAs of 180, 720, 1440, and 2880ms. Participants in 1b did the experiment in groups of 2, all in the same room.
Conditions were as follows: All cues were uninformative.


Gaze Back: Participants are cued to shift their attention, and then the cue shifts back to centre, causing attention to re-orient to centre.


No Return: Participants are cued, and the gaze cue remains looking in the same direction through the remainder of the trial.


Cue Back: Participants are cued, and then the gaze cue outline brightens to exogenously cue people to return their attention to fixation.


If it is true that gaze-cuing causes attention to remain oriented in place and that is why it doesn't show IOR, then the Gaze Back and Cue Back conditions should show IOR. This should be obvious at longer SOAs.
Results Summary: No IOR observed in any of the three conditions. Gaze-cuing did provide facilitation at early SOAs, but no IOR.
Discussion Summary: It is an open question whether gaze-cuing is more like endogenous or exogenous orienting. It simply could be a hybrid.
There are two main reasons to believe it may be more like exogenous orienting:


Orienting to gaze is rapid when in response to uninformative, peripheral cues.


When gaze is given a counter-predictive meaning, the initial attention shift is in the direction of the gaze. Therefore, the initial response to a gaze cue is reflexive.


There are three main reasons to believe it may be more like endogenous orienting:


Gaze cues are rarely followed by IOR, unlike exogenous cues which are always followed by IOR.


Like centrally presented, informative cues, central gaze cues do not directly stimulate the periphery.


Vecera \& Rizzo (2006) had a frontal patient who failed to orient to gaze cues while still orienting normally to exogenous cues. The patient also failed to orient to central cues, which indicates that gaze-cuing shares control mechanisms with both endogenous and exogenous orienting.


Future Directions
We must figure out whether gaze-cuing is more like endogenous or exogenous orienting.
Klein (1994) showed that endogenous attention interacts with nonspatial expectancies, whereas exogenous attention is additive with nonspatial expectancies.
Briand \& Klein (1987) showed that endogenous attention is additive with opportunities for illusory conjunctions, whereas exogenous attention interacts with opportunities for illusory conjunctions.
Gaze cuing must be combined with the methods of Klein (1994) and Briand \& Klein (1987).
If gaze cuing is interactive with nonspatial expectancies and additive with opportunities for illusory conjunctions, then we can conclude that gaze cuing is more like endogenous attention.
If gaze cuing is additive with nonspatial expectancies and interactive with opportunities for illusory conjunctions, then gaze cuing is more like exogenous attention.
**************************
STUDIES TO READ NEXT
***************************
Studies on the differences between endogenous and exogenous attention:
Briand, K., \& Klein, R. (1987). Is Posner's "Beam" the Same as Treisman's "Glue"? Journal of Experimental Psychology. Human Perception and Performance, 13(2), 228-241. https://web-a-ebscohost-com.ezproxy.library.dal.ca/ehost/detail/detail?vid=1\&sid=136b62a1-b23d-471c-a588-75cfc40d8f31\%40sdc-v-sessmgr03\&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ\%3d\%3d\#AN=1987-23943-001\&db=pdh
Klein, R. M. (1994). Perceptual-motor expectancies interact with covert visual orienting under conditions of endogenous but not exogenous control. Canadian Journal of Experimental Psychology, 48(2), 167-81. https://ezproxy.library.dal.ca/login?url=https://www-proquest-com.ezproxy.library.dal.ca/scholarly-journals/perceptual-motor-expectancies-interact-with/docview/200396291/se-2?accountid=10406
Klein R.M., \& Shore, D.I. (2000). Relations among modes of visual orienting. Control of Cognitive Processes, 18, 195-208. https://www.researchgate.net/publication/247382846\_Relations\_among\_modes\_of\_visual\_orienting
*************************
CLARIFICATION NOTES
**************************
Posner Cueing Paradigm: Explanation from Wikipedia


Cues:


Endogenous cues: Presented at centre


Exogenous cues: Presented peripherally




Valid, Invalid, and Neutral trials:


Valid: Stimulus appears on side indicated by cue


Invalid: Stimulus appears on side opposite to that indicated by cue


Neutral: No cues, just stimulus


Or, less commonly, cues that alert the participant that a stimulus is coming, but don't tell which side


E.g., Double-sided arrow






Posner used 80\% valid, 20\% invalid in his experiments to get participants used to following the cue




Informative and Uninformative cueing:


Informative cues occur when the ratio of Valid/Invalid trials is such that Valid trials are more likely (typically, this is 75/25 or 80/20, the latter being Posner's favourite).


Uninformative cues occur when the ratio of Valid/Invalid trials is set so that the type of trial is random (so, 50/50).




Stimulus onset asynchronies (SOAs):


Time interval between onset of cue and onset of target.




**************************
INTRODUCTION
**************************


Uninformative peripheral cues can cause rapid automatic orienting at short SOAs, such that targets presented near the stimulated location are processed more efficiently than farther away ones.


Gaze cueing first started as a study in joint attention in infants.


Infants as young as 6mos can look faster at a target that was gaze cued.


Question: Did the gaze cue orient attention, or did it activate an oculomotor program to look in the same direction? Either way, orienting was enhanced.




Friesen \& Kingstone (1998): First gaze cueing orienting study in adults.


Reflexive orienting is triggered by a nonpredictive gaze.


At early SOAs, there was a reliable facilitation from gaze cues.


Did not find IOR at long SOAs. This is strange.




Why doesn't gaze cueing show IOR?


Posner \& Cohen (1984): If attention remains at a cued location, we don't see IOR.


So, they drew attention back to centre with two methods:


Face brightens (exogenous).


Targets were more likely at fixation than at two peripheral locations (endogenous).




It could be that after an uninformative gaze cue, attention stays at the cued location rather than returning to neutral.






If gaze cueing is exogenously controlled, then we should expect that attention would remain oriented at the cued location, given that the eyes keep gazing in that direction. This could prevent IOR.


 
Current Study


Uninformative gaze cues presented at various intervals prior to target presentation.


To replicate finding of orienting to gaze cues.




Three conditions:


Two conditions: Return attention to fixation.


Gaze Back: Gaze returned to centre.


Cue Back: Brightness of face cues return to fixation.




One condition:Do not return attention to fixation. 


No Return: Maintain attention at cued location using face that continues to gaze in cued direction for duration of trial.






Hypotheses:


Gaze Back and Cue Back conditions should show IOR, No Return condition should not show IOR.




Special methods:


Nonspatial discrimination task (A kind of Choice task): Two-choice response (Is triangle pointing up or down?)


This avoids possibility that RT differences between cued and uncued targets are due to response bias (which happens w/detection tasks) or cue-induced response activation (which happens w/localization tasks).


Also enables us to see if gaze cueing interacts w/the Simon effect.






**************************
METHOD
**************************
Procedure


Fig. 2:







Experiment 1a: Administered individually. Each person completes experiment alone in a room.


Intervals: 90, 270, 630, 1350ms


Written as SOAs: 180, 360, 720, 1440ms






Experiment 1b: Administered in groups of 20 students in one room.


Intervals: 90, 630, 1350, 2790ms


Written as SOAs: 180, 720, 1440, 2880ms






Face/Target remains on screen for 1500ms or until participant responds


Valid/Invalid: 50/50. Therefore, gaze cues are entirely uninformative.


Participant task: Indicate orienrtation of target shape using number keys ("1" for upward pointing triangle, "2" for downward).


Participants told to fixate on nose of face at all times.


Participants told that direction of gaze was uninformative and that two types of triangles were equally likely to appear.


**************************
RESULTS
**************************
Experiment 1a


No main effect of Return condition.


Main effects of SOAs: Longer RTs for shortest interval than the others.


Main effect of Cue condition: Faster RTs to validly cued targets.


Main effect of Simon congruency: Faster RTs when target and response were on same side.


Interaction between Cue Condition and Simon congruency: Larger Simon effect at uncued location.


Marginal interaction between Cue Condition and Return Condition.


Accuracy:


Significant effect of Simon congruency (more accurate when target was on same side).


Significant interaction between Cue condition and Simon congruency.


Fig. 4:





From most accurate to least accurate, and from fastest to slowest RT:


Valid cue, Incongruent Simon trial.


Invalid cue, Incongruent Simon trial.


Valid cue, Congruent Simon trial.


Invalid cue, Congruent Simon trial.












Experiment 1b


No main effect of Return condition.


Main effect of SOAs: Longer RTs for shortest interval than the others.


Main effect of Cue condition: Faster RT to validly cued targets.


Main effect of Simon congruency: Faster RTs when target and response were on same side.


Interaction between Cue condition and Simon congruency: Larger Simon effect at uncued location.


Accuracy:


Significant effect of SOA: Less accurate at shortest interval.


Significant effect of Simon congruency: Less accurate response when target and response were on opposite sides.


Main effect of Cue condition: Accuracy slightly higher on valid than on invalid trials.




Combined analyses


Participants in Experiment 1b were significantly faster than those in 1a, and were non-significantly less accurate by 9\% (when compared across common SOAs).


Attributable to Experiment 1b being put in a group, therefore being more competitive.




**************************
DISCUSSION
**************************


No significant differences in patterns of results for common SOAs of the two experiments, so it doesn't matter if you use a group or individualized administration. Justifies collapsing the two experiments for the purposes of power.


Significant facilitation from uninformative gaze cues at SOAs up to 1440ms.


No significant IOR detected at any SOA.


Facilitation from gaze cues interacted with Simon effect (target/response location congruity) such that Simon effect was significantly reduced at cued location.


Timecourse of Gaze Cuing


No IOR for gaze cuing.


If we look at the time course in Fig. 1, exogenous orienting shows pretty clear IOR at longer SOAs, whereas orienting to uninformative gaze cues does not show any IOR at all. The time course is radically different.


Is Gaze-Directed Attention More Like Endogenous or Exogenous Attention?


Case for exogenous:


In response to an uninformative, peripherally presented cue, orienting to gaze is rapid.


Even when gaze is given a counter-predictive meaning (gaze left signals right handed target), initial attention shift is in the direction of the gaze, so the initial response is reflexive.




Case for endogenous:


Gaze cues are rarely followed by IOR, unlike exogenous cues.


Like centrally presented, informative cues, central gaze cues do not directly stimulate the periphery.


Vecera \& Rizzo (2006): Frontal patient who failed to orient to gaze cues while still orienting normally to exogenous cues. Patient also failed to orient to central cues, indicating gaze cuing shares endogenous control mechanisms.




Gaze Cuing and the Simon Effect


Gaze cuing is distinguished from typical exo and endo controlled shifts of attention.


The pattern of interaction seen in Fig. 4 is different from typical exo and endo shifts.




**************************
CONCLUSION
**************************


Whether gaze is endo or exo must be further explored.


Recommended studies:


Differences between endo and exo: Klein \& Shore (2000); Klein (2004).


E.g. Endogenous attention interacts with nonspatial expectancies while exogenous attention is additive with them. See Klein (1994).


Endo is additive with opportunities for illusory conjunctions, exo interacts with them. See Briand \& Klein (1987).






Would orienting to gaze cues look more like endo or exo if combined with nonspatial expectancies and opportunities for illusory conjunctions?


 
 
 
 
