@article{briand_is_1987,
	title = {Is {Posner}'s 'beam' the same as {Treisman}'s 'glue'?: {On} the relation between visual orienting and feature integration theory},
	volume = {13},
	issn = {0096-1523},
	shorttitle = {Is {Posner}'s 'beam' the same as {Treisman}'s 'glue'?},
	url = {http://ezproxy.library.dal.ca/login?url=https://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=pdh&AN=1987-23943-001&site=ehost-live},
	doi = {10.1037/0096-1523.13.2.228},
	abstract = {In the present study we investigated whether the visually allocated 'beam' studied by Posner and others is the same visual attentional resource that performs the role of feature integration in Treisman's model. Subjects were cued to attend to a certain spatial location by a visual cue, and performance at expected and unexpected stimulus locations was compared. Subjects searched for a target letter (R) with distractor letters that either could give rise to illusory conjunctions (PQ) or could not (PB). Results from three separate experiments showed that orienting attention in response to central cues (endogenous orienting) showed similar effects for both conjunction and feature search. However, when attention was oriented with peripheral visual cues (exogenous orienting), conjunction search showed larger effects of attention than did feature search. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
	number = {2},
	urldate = {2021-09-24},
	journal = {Journal of Experimental Psychology: Human Perception and Performance},
	author = {Briand, Kevin A. and Klein, Raymond M.},
	month = may,
	year = {1987},
	note = {Publisher: American Psychological Association},
	keywords = {allocation of attention in visual space, Attention, Canada, college students, Cues, Discrimination Learning, Fixation, Ocular, Form Perception, Humans, Models, Optical Illusions, Orientation, Pattern Recognition, Visual, Perceptual Masking, Reaction Time, tests of Treisman's feature integration theory vs Posner's visual orienting model, Theories, Visual Perception, notion},
	pages = {228--241},
	annote = {STUDY NOTES: EXPERIMENT 1
*************************


"Taking experiments 4 and 5 into account, we need an experiment that compares performance in detection of targets that appear at cued or uncued locations, at the same time controlling for such things as processing demands of the task."


My gaze cueing experiment is only possible b/c of this paper, and only possible b/c it sought to clarify this confound in Treisman's experiments. Could be good for honours proposal.




*************************
STUDY SUMMARY
*************************
 
Is Posner's beam the same as Treisman's glue?


If we compare stimulus sets containing no possibility for illusory conjunction (RPB) and stimulus sets involving possibility for illusory conjunction (RPQ) and use the Posner cuing paradigm:


We should expect an interaction between cue validity and stimulus set.


I.e., we'd expect reaction time to be slower for cases where there are illusory conjunctions.


If the effect is merely additive, we'd expect RT to be fastest for valid cues, second fastest for neutral cues, and slowest for invalid cues, for both groups, and the slope of that slowing in RT shouldn't be radically steeper for the RPQ condition. I.e., if Posner's beam is NOT the same as Treisman's glue, we'd expect no interaction between stimulus set and cue validity.




Experiments 1-3 used central cues, and just found an additive effect. But, they were endogenous studies.


Experiment 4 used peripheral cues, and found an interaction. That's exogenous.


So, for endogenous orienting, Posner's beam is NOT the same as Treisman's glue. For exogenous orienting, Posner's beam is the same as Treisman's glue.


*************************
INTRODUCTION
*************************
The Past


Treisman's FIT vs Posner's visual orienting (PVO):


FIT: Attention is necessary to "glue" together properties into objects.


PVO: Attention is like a beam which is oriented selectively to certain areas.




Is Posner's beam the same as Treisman's glue?


 
Posner's Visual Orienting Model


Neutral cue, valid cue, and invalid cue.


Benefits of valid cue are calculated by difference in reaction time and/or accuracy between valid cue and neutral cue.


Costs of invalid cue are calculated by difference in reaction time and/or accuracy between invalid cue and neutral cue.


Overall cuing effect: Instead of neutral cue, you take total costs plus benefits (CBs) and calculate based on that.




Posner concluded that attention is like a spotlight. "Attention can be likened to a postlight that enhances the efficiency of detection of events within its beam" (Posner et al., 1980, p. 172).


Findings suggesting a spotlight:


Attention can't be easily allocated to non-adjacent regions.


Performance improvements gradually decrease as one moves away from the attended location, and this fall-off is steeper near the more densely represented fovea.


Shifts may take place with a fixed velocity.


Attention moves through intermediate positions.




Central cues occurring at fixation orient attention differently than do peripheral cues occurring at potential parafoveal locations.


Best peripheral cues are ones that we'd expect to draw eye movements. Orienting in response to peripheral cues is relatively automatic, compared to orienting in response to central cues which is strategic.






 
Treisman's Feature Integration Theory


There are separable dimensions (shape, colour, etc). Within these dimensions, there are values, which are features. Features are coded pre-attentively/automatically, and then conjunctions of features are synthesized in three ways:


Features coded are fit into pre-directed object frames.


Attention is directed to the location of a particular feature and serves to integrate it with other features present at the same location.


If attention isn't used, or if unexpected features occur, the coded features may conjoin on their own, resulting in illusory conjunctions.




Three paradigms for investigation: These are all indirect methods, where the manipulation of attention is inferred rather than directed.


Target search: Subjects look for specific target in an array full of distractors. Critical comparison is in searching for a conjunction compared with searching for a disjunction of features.


Texture segregation: Subjects report whether the border separating sections of a texture from one another is horizontal or vertical. Response latencies are faster when texture segregation is based on features than when it is based on conjunctions of features.


Identify and locate either feature targets or conjunction targets in a display of distractors. Probability of correct identification given incorrect location was greater than chance for feature targets but not for conjunction targets, so features can be identified w/out knowing their location but conjunctions cannot.




Paradigm for directly manipulating attention:


Studies probability of illusory conjunctions when stimulus duration is very short and attention is misdirected or overloaded.


Treisman \& Schmidt experiment 4: Array of four objects was displayed, each defined by combos of the dimensions of shape,  size, color, and solidity. Two distractor digits appear flanking the shapes. Instructions to report digits were intended to prevent subjects from focusing full attention on the display. Immediately after display offset, a probe appeared, and subjects reported the item shown at that location. Illusory conjunctions outnumber feature errors.


Experiment 5: Pre-cued location of targets rather than post-cue, and eliminated flanking numbers. Conjunction errors didn't occur, and errors tended to be based on feature intrusions.




Experiments 4 and 5 can't be used to demonstrate that misorienting in visual space increases likelihood of illusory conjunctions, b/c they confound the selectivity and capacity aspects of attention: Pre-cuing allows for greater selectivity in orienting, and also lowers capacity for what needs to be processed, whereas post-cuing doesn't allow for selectivity and leaves capacity at having to process all four items to identify the target. Therefore unclear whether illusory conjunctions occurred b/c attention was misdirected, overloaded, or both.




Taking experiments 4 and 5 into account, we need an experiment that compares performance in detection of targets that appear at cued or uncued locations, at the same time controlling for such things as processing demands of the task.


 
Rationale


Posner's system investigates attention's role in enhancing the detectability of stimuli in an uncluttered field, exploring properties of attention such as the duration and velocity of its movement and restrictions to its distributions in space.


Treisman's fiew emphasizes attention's role in conjoining free-floating attributes during visual search, and her program is aimed at converging evidence for this role.


Are the two programs exploring the same system from different perspectives? Is Posner's beam the same as Treisman's glue?


Treisman says no, arguing that she studies the type of attention that refers to selective scanning of competing external stimuli, whereas Posner's is for priming or expectancy effects which selectively preactivate particular perceptual dimensions.




Present study hypothesizes that the two systems are the same. Attention is a limited-capacity mechanism that can be allocated spatially. This is consistent with Posner. Furthermore, it would be unparsimonius to posit two separate systems.


Present study will combine Posner's orienting paradigm with a variant of Treisman's feature/conjunction task to test the hypothesis.


We should expect there to be a benefit to reaction time from central cues whether it be for feature search or conjunction search. Valid central cues should provide the biggest benefit, neutral cues faster than the invalid cues, but the benefit of cuing should be stronger for feature integration than for feature search, if Posner's beam is the same as Treisman's glue.




Target letter: R


Distractors: PB and PQ.


Task harder with PQ b/c of illusory conjunctions.




*************************
EXPERIMENT 1A
*************************


R isn't present in display. Performance should be worse with PQ stimuli than with PB, relative to appropriate controls. Should be a tendency for this difference when letters appear in unexpected location.


Critical data: Costs and benefits in reaction time and/or accuracy for the PB and PQ stimuli.


RT: Changes in probability of illusory conjunctions could show up in RT, b/c participants may slow down to reduce errors.


Accuracy: Less accurate for PQ than PQ means illusory conjunctions.




 
Method


Apparatus:


Subjects hold two remote control like objects:


Responding hand: Two buttons, one close to subject and one further away, each pressed by index and middle fingers respectively.


Nonresponding hand: Third button on a vertical bar for initiating trials.




Eye monitors used.




Stimuli: Upper case R, Q, P, and B shown on oscilloscope from distance of 49 cm, visual angle 0.53 degrees X 0.72 degrees.


840 trials:


240 trials with neutral prime (+) so that letters appeared equally often on left and right side.


480 trials with valid primes: Letters appeared in location indicated by the arrow, with equal number of left and right pointing valid cues.


120 trials with invalid cues: Letters appeared in location opposite to that indicated by the arrow.




Proportion of valid and invalid trials ensured that when an arrow was the warning signal, 80\% of the time it was a valid cue, and 20\% of the time an invalid cue.


12 possible permutations of two letters from four, each shown an equal number of times in left and right locations on the screen. For a given permutation in a given location there were 10 neutral cues, 20 valid cues, and 5 invalid cues. 12 permutations X 35 trials X 2 locations = 840 trials.




Procedure:


Trials begin with appearance of the fixation field, which also served as the intertrial stimulus.


When subjects fixated the center dot, they initiated the trial by pressing the center toggle switch button.


500 ms after pressing, warning cue appears superimposed over center dot, remains for 1000 ms.


Stimulus display appears for 100 ms, during which time the left and right dots were removed from the screen.


Subjects must determine whether an R was present in the display, and respond as quickly as possible by pressing the near button on the response board (for R) or far button (no R).


Subjects told they must keep fixated at center at all times during the trial. They were told the probabilities and were encouraged to direct their attention to the location indicated by the arrow without moving their eyes.


Three blocks of 280 trials were conducted on different days. Subjects began with calibration of the eye movement monitor followed by practice blocks of 10 trials until they scored at least 7 correct in two consecutive blocks.




*************************
EXPERIMENT 1B
*************************
