	pages = {694--724},
	annote = {******************
INTRODUCTION
******************

"What can gaze cueing reveal about the origins and neural bases of symbolic attention cueing?" (1)

 
Gaze Perception

How do infants achieve gaze perception? Gaze perception is the ability to use the eyes to derive information necessary for "skills in engaging in collaboration, deception, and inference of intentions and mental states" (2).
The Neural Basis of Gaze Perception (2):

Superior temporal sulcus (STS) codes biological motion and static biological information such as eye position (2-3).
Baron-Cohen (1995) proposed that "encoding of another's eye-gaze direction is an integral part of theory of mind" (3).
It seems that gaze direction is used differently depending on the context and perceived goals of a person's actions (3).
The amygdala is necessary for judging gaze direction and facial expression (4).
Parietal cortex necessary for orienting, specifically intraparietal sulcus (IPS) which is necessary for spatial processing and covert orienting (4).


How is Accurate Gaze Perception Achieved? (4):

The structure of the eye is important. The human eye is largely white, and then descends slowly into a darkest point, making it easier to track gaze shifts. And it's mainly the geometry of the eye that does this rather than the luminance (4-5).

Note: This geometry is probably what makes schematic faces good gaze cues.


The presence of objects also affects perceived gaze direction. So it's not just the geometry of the eye, but also predicting an object that a person is looking at, is involved in perceiving gaze (5).


What Are the Effects of Eye Contact? (5):

Eye contact is both a sign of aggressive approach (as in other animals), and a signal of attraction (for humans) (5-6).

Males (but not females) rate female faces that shift gaze toward them as more attractive, and less attractive when gaze is shifted away (6).


The presence of a central face with eyes pointing forward makes it harder for people to attend to peripheral objects (6).

"direct gaze both captures attention and delays disengagement of attention from the face stimulus" (6).


Haley and Fessler (2005): When you have people play a computer game where they can choose to share money, they share more money when the background on the computer contains schematic eyes than when it doesn't (6-7).


Gaze Perception and Joint Attention in Development (7):

Infants prefer faces with eyes (7).
At 4 months, infants have deeper face processing of faces with direct gaze, and at 5 months they get good at discriminating very fine horizontal deviations (5 degrees) of eye gaze. Still, it may not be until 3 y/o that children can determine whether an adult is making eye contact or where they're looking (7).
Hood, Willen, and Driver (1998): 3 m/o infants have facilitated saccades to gaze direction when faces are presented on a computer screen (7).

Farroni, Massaccesi, et al. (2004): Neonates must see eyes move to follow the gaze of another person (7).

Moore, Angelopoulos, and Bennett (1997) found that 9 m/o infants could use static gaze cues if they'd already developed the ability to use motion gaze cues (7).
"gaze contact–engaging attention on the face–followed by pupil motion, is vital to give rise to the more complex behaviors involved in joint attention in infancy" (8).




At 12-18 m/o, infants specifically use eye movements for gaze cues rather than just head turns, b/c if a person's eyes are closed and their head turns, the infant doesn't follow (8).
At 7 m/o, infants prefer to follow the gaze of a neutral face rather than a happy or sad face (8).
Gaze following at 6 m/o correlates w/vocabulary size at 18 m/o (8).
Development of joint attention at 20 m/o predicts theory of mind at 44 m/o (8).
By 9 m/o, infants correctly orient to the object adults are looking at rather than just to the closest object in spatial vicinity (8-9).
By 3-4 y/o, infants can use gaze to predict a person's intentions. E.g., If Charlie is looking at a chocolate bar, he probably wants the bar (9).

This is vulnerable to interference until 5 y/o. If an arrow next to the face is pointing the opposite direction, children under 5 fail to appropriately attribute intentions to the face (9).




