STUDY SUMMARY
--------------
Short Summary
Global estimates of youth depression and anxiety have doubled during the pandemic, to 1/4 and 1/5 children respectively experiencing clinical elevation (in a meta-analysis of range from Jan. 2020 to March 2021). As the pandemic goes on, this gets worse. Girls are more vulnerable to depression and anxiety. Older children are more vulnerable to depression but not anxiety. Authors chalk up the general increase primarily to social isolation, school closures (leading both to social isolation and lack of access to mental health care, which 80\% of children access at school). Parents should ensure to maintain routines. Practitioners must offer appropriate mental health referrals. Policy makers must consider school and recreational closures a last resort. Tele health could be used for wide scale mental health service delivery.
Noteworthy Information

Studies in this meta-analysis were conducted sometime between January 1, 2020, and March 8, 2021.

Study Question

Meta-analysis
How has youth mental health been affected, worldwide, during the COVID-19 pandemic?

Results

29 samples, N = 80,879 youth
Doubling of youth clinically elevated depression and anxiety worldwide

Depression: Now 1 in 4 children (Prepandemic, 12.9\%; During pandemic, 25.2\%)

May be b/c children are socially isolated; lack of support networks in schools and friend groups; school closures, b/c schools are primary source of psychological care for 80\% of children.


Anxiety: Now 1 in 5 children (Prepandemic, 11.6\%; During pandemic, 20.5\%)

May be b/c children are socially isolated; lack of support networks in schools and friend groups; school closures, b/c schools are primary source of psychological care for 80\% of children.




Moderator variables:

Depression:

Time: Longer the pandemic went on, the worse things got

