Sex: Females more likely to experience depressive symptoms.

May be b/c of biological susceptibility, lower baseline self-esteem, higher likelihood of having experienced interpersonal violence, exposure to stress b/c of gender inequity.


Age: NOT A MODERATOR FOR ANXIETY.

May be b/c younger and older children experience anxiety for similar reasons. Older children may notice parental stress more and be more bothered by the global situation. Younger children may be especially disrupted by changes to routine.







Implications

Families w/more routines had lower child depression and conduct problems.

May be best to maintain good routines, particularly for schoolwork, sleep, screen use, and physical activity.


Clinical references ought to be made for children that need it.
Social isolation risk to youth must be considered by policy makers.

School closures and halting of recreational activities should be considered a last resort.


Tele mental health a good opportunity for widescale mental health service delivery.

Study Limitations

Not very much data from underrepresented countries; hard to understand cross-regional differences.
Studies in meta-analysis were mostly cross-sectional; longitudinal data is needed, especially w/baseline estimates of anxiety and depression.
More studies needed with racial, ethnic, and gender diversity.
Self-report measures were used, and they were primarily administered to parents. Studies w/criterion standard assessments needed for finer results w/more understanding of other possible mental health problems at play.

