STUDY SUMMARY
--------------
Notable Information

Study conducted from May to August 2020 in the United States

Study Summary
A big sample of youth (7983) in the United States who were participating in a prior study joined a study on the effects of COVID-19 on mental health. The youths filled out three surveys during the months of May to August 2020 (survey 1, May 2020; survey 2, June 2020; survey 3, August 2020). The surveys included measurements of overall mood (which was also compared to prepandemic baseline) as well as the impact of COVID-19 on fears, worries, etc. The study found that generally speaking, youth mental health scores improved overall in the late Spring/early Summer of the pandemic. COVID-19-related fears/worries/stress, however, increased, and this was particularly noteable in minority youths (Asians and Blacks, who experienced discrimination) as well as in older adolescents, girls, and those with higher baseline internalizing symptoms (the latter 3 of which were also at greater risk of poorer overall mental health beforehand and during the months of the pandemic). Children with higher ACEs were more vulnerable to poorer mental health measures and COVID-19-related fears/worries/stress. Children with parents that had a high-school diploma or higher education experienced less fear of the virus. The study was limited, in that it wasn't as diverse as the previous ABCD study cohort, and it also didn't include as many children from lower-income backgrounds.
The authors say in the discussion, "Notably, across the early months of the pandemic onset (summer 2020), youth reported improvements in mental health, suggesting potential resiliency as the pandemic continues." It appears that they're suggesting resiliency rather than trying to demonstrate it. I think this may be confounded by a few things: COVID-19 cases in the United States remained relatively steady and low until October 2020, when they started to climb. Furthermore, cases were very low in most states for that period (although they were interpreted to be high at the time), with New York, Florida, Texas, and California making up huge numbers of the already relatively low (compared to later in the pandemic) case counts during that summer. Things really didn't start getting absolutely nuts until the Fall of 2020, so suggesting the results as a sign of resiliency going forward was fine for its time, but it simply didn't hold up as the pandemic continued.
Study Questions

Do ACEs predict worse mental health outcomes during the COVID-19 pandemic?
Does racial-ethnic minority status predict a stronger relationship between ACEs and mental health symptoms during the pandemic?

Methods

Study conducted from May to August 2020 in the United States
Children enrolled in the Adolescent Brain Cognitive Development (ABCD) Study: Nationwide United States study
Used school-based recruitment.
Study had baseline mental health data from earlier ABCD study, which it then compared to later COVID-19 survey data.
Demographic info (including family job/wage loss and changes in school environment) were reported by parents in the COVID-19 impact survey.

Results

N = 7983; recruited between 2016-2018 at ages 9 or 10.

Full ABCD study included 11,880 children. Of that cohort, 7983 participated in this study.
In this study, compared to the ABCD cohort the children were more likely to be White and to have higher parental education and household income. They were also less likely to have a history of ACE.


Sadness Scale:

ACEs: ACEs predicted greater sadness
Time: Sadness decreased
Race/ethnicity: Race was related to sadness. Black youths reported less sadness than non-Hispanic White youths.
Demographics: Older youths, girls, and those with greater internalizing scores reported greater sadness.


Positive Affect Scale:

ACEs: ACEs predicted less sadness.
Race/ethnicity: Race was related to positive affect. Black youths reported more positive affect than non-Hispanic Whites.
Demographics: Older youths, girls, and those with greater internalizing scores reported less positive mood.


Fear/Worry Scale:

ACEs: ACEs predicted more fear and worry.
Race/ethnicity: Race was related to fear/worry. Youths from minority racial or multiracial backgrounds reported greater fear/worry from COVID than White youths.
Demographics: Youths with household incomes between \$50k and \$100k as well as youths with household incomes ≥\$100k had greater internalizing scores. Girls reported greater fear and worry.


Anger/Frustration:

ACEs: ACEs predicted greater anger and frustration.
Time: Anger and frustration decreased over time.
Race/ethnicity: Race was related to anger/frustration. Black youths reported less anger and frustration than non-Hispanic White youths.
Demographics: Girls, youth with household incomes ≥\$100k, and those with greater internalizing scores reported more anger and frustration.


Perceived Stress Scale:

ACEs: ACEs predicted greater stress.
Time: Stress decreased over time.
Demographics: Older youths, girls, and those with greater internalizing scores reported greater stress.


Coronavirus Health Impact Survey COVID-19 Worry:

ACEs: ACEs did not predict COVID-19-related worry.
Time: Worry decreased over time.
Race/ethnicity: Significantly related to worry. Asian American and Black youths as well as other minority youths reported greater COVID worry, as well as Latinx youths.
ACE x race x time: High ACE Black youths were the only group that reported a reduction in COVID worry from survey 2 to survey 3.
Demographics: Girls and those with family wage loss and greater internalizing scores reported more COVID-19-related worry.


Coronavirus Health Impact Survey COVID-19 Uncertainty Stress:

ACEs: ACEs predicted greater COVID-19-related uncertainty stress.
Race/ethnicity: Race significantly related to stress. Minority youths reported more COVID-19-related uncertainty stress.
Demographics: Girls, those with family wage loss, and those with greater internalizing scores reported more COVID-19 uncertainty stress.


Fear of Illness and Virus Evaluation Scale: Impact of Illness and Virus Fears:

ACEs: ACEs predicted greater virus fears on well-being.
Time: Virus fears decreased over time.
Race/ethnicity: Race significantly related to impact. Minority youths reported greater impact of the virus on their well-being.
Demographics: Girls and those with higher internalizing scores reported greater impact of virus-related fears. Youths with well-educated parents (high school completion onwards) reported less impact of virus-related fears on their well-being.



Key Findings

After controlling for essentially everything, greater ACEs predicted worse outcomes on everything except COVID-19-related worry.
Mood symptoms and COVID-19-related distress improved across the three waves of data collection from May to August 2020.

May be b/c those who experienced greater early life stress were able to rebound faster.


Racial and ethnic minorities more likely to be impacted by COVID-19-related stress and worry.

May be b/c minority children's families are more likely to be exposed to the effects of COVID-19, including in infection, hospitalization, and mortality.
May also be b/c of racial discrimination, whether it be b/c of anti-Asian hate or responses to Black Lives Matter. Asians and Blacks reported more COVID-19-related racial discrimination, and this was a big predictor of COVID-19-related worry.


Greater pre-pandemic internalizing symptoms predicted worse outcomes on essentially every measure.
Females reported poorer mood and greater distress on COVID-19-related measures.
The improvement in mental health during the early months of the pandemic onset could suggest potential resiliency as the pandemic continues.

Study Limitations

Key limitation I see is that the sample was undersampled in minoritized and low-income families relative to the overall ABCD Study cohort.
},
