Notable Information
This study is very long, and since I'm only writing about youth, I'll focus on the results for children, adolescents, and college students. It covers short and long term data (up until {\textasciitilde}September 2021).
Study Summary
Past research has shown that overall, people have been fairly resilient, recovering quickly from COVID-19-related measures.  However, adolescents and health care personnel have been severely impacted by the pandemic. "The mental health of children, adolescents, and students has been particularly affected by the pandemic" (23). For children, parental stress, loss of regular health care, etc. affected mental health. In adolescents, parental stress was less a determinant of resilience than it was for children. Even in the early days of the pandemic (Spring 2020), adolescents were experiencing almost double the typical rates for anxiety and depression, perhaps upwards of 43.7\% for depression symptoms and 37.4\% for anxiety symptoms. For adolescents, risk factors included being female, lacking physical exercise, and lacking social support. There were, however, conflicting results, with many studies also suggesting that the vast majority of adolescents didn't experience worsening mental health during COVID (at least in the early days), and there may have been decreases in suicide rates briefly. In college students, many experienced anxiety and depression, although sometimes this was accompanied with less internalizing symptoms and more externalizing symptoms. Girls and those with less social support were more at risk. Those with good coping strategies (relaxation, routines, exercise, etc.) were protective.
Generally speaking, the pandemic had negative effects on mental health for children, adolescents, and youth. But these risks varied a lot within groups. For children and younger adolescents, parental stress and decreased physical activity were important risk factors. But in adolescents and students, COVID-19-and academic related worries, family conflict, loneliness, and lack of health behaviours were important risk factors. Generally, youth were vulnerable during COVID, but those with coping strategies could find signs of resilience.
