Short Summary
Overall, it appears that in the first wave of COVID (February to July 2020), youth (0-19) were more likely to experience mental health problems (18-60\% of youth; higher than prepandemic estimates). Estimates for depression symptoms were around 25\%, and for anxiety symptoms they were around 20\%. There isn't an indicator that suicide increased during the first wave. Reports of child abuse and medical referrals dropped a lot (27\% reduction, Florida; 36\% reduction, UK, respectively) but these also coincided with school closures, and it appears that school reports of these issues dropped by around 50\%. There was also a 50-65\% reduction in self-harm admissions and a 40\% reduction in psychiatric admissions, which, in the context of increasing psychological distress and decreasing access to school-based reports, suggests that some youth had mental health needs that went unmet in the first wave. It appears that the average amount of physical activity in children dropped, but if you break it down some kids (36-47\%) were exercising less and some (24-25\%) were exercising more. Percent of children with screen time over 3 hours increased (30-50\%) but few studies separated screen time for school from screen time for social media. It's very difficult to separate the effects of school closures from the broader social lockdowns because every study coincided with social lockdown. Still, it appears that loss of daily routine was potentially damaging (perhaps to behavioral health in children) and it looks like school closures were responsible for most of the reduction in social mixing amongst youth (who experienced less of a drop in social mixing than all other age groups).
Noteworthy Information

N = 79,781 children; 18,028 parents

Across 36 studies


Only during first wave of COVID (February to July 2020)

Study Question

How have school closures and social lockdowns affected youth mental health? A systematic review

Results

Broadly speaking: Adverse mental health symptoms; bad health behaviours (higher screen time, lower physical activity).
Mental Health and Well-Being:

Suicide:

No significant increase in suicide in England; but COVID/lockdown factors deemed to account for 48\% of 26 suicide deaths during lockdown.
One Canadian study found that 17.5\% of individuals aged 16-18 years old reported suicidal ideation in the past week, compared to 6\% in the pre-COVID-19 estimates.


Mental Health Symptoms:

Some studies have reported higher ranges of mental health symptoms (44\%+), but for the most part, it looks like depression symptoms float around 25\% and anxiety symptoms around 20\%.
Overall, it looks like most studies reported higher symptoms of stress, anxiety, and depression as well as behavioural issues than pre-COVID. But a handful of studies did find no difference, and some even found slight improvement.
18-60\% of children and adolescents scored above thresholds for risk of psychological difficulties (higher than pre-COVID).


Well-being:

Very small number of low quality studies on overall well-being; looks like they reported minor worsening of well-being scores.


Child abuse:

Reported child abuse cases dropped a lot (around 27\%), but the majority of child abuse cases in these areas (Florida and the UK) are reported by schools, and the number of school-based reports dropped dramatically.
Medical referrals for children dropped a lot (36\% in the UK), but again, over half of the referrals from schools vanished upon school closure.


Sleep:

Studies were all over the place. I can't draw any conclusions other than that it looks like there might not have been a difference.




Health Behaviors:

Physical activity:

It looks like in many places, the average amount of physical activity kids were getting dropped. However, this is because it dropped for many kids (between 36 and 47\% of kids) but also rose for many kids (24-25\%). Still, it seems that overall the average physical activity dropped.


Screen Time and Social Media:

Screen time data sucks because it reports an increase, but the studies didn't consistently break apart overall screen time and kind of screen usage (e.g. at home learning vs cell phone).
Percent of children using social media for more than 3 hours a day increased, somewhere between 30 and 50\% on weekdays.

Doesn't look like there's an increase on weekends.






Associations with Socioeconomic Status:

Evidence not very good. Many studies didn't break down at all; some found lower education families had worse anxiety; some found no difference.
Overall very few studies on this.



Implications

Almost all studies documented poorer mental health and well-being compared to pre-COVID estimates.
None of the studies were capable of separating school closure effects from effects of social lockdowns.

Authors say there are strong theoretical reasons to believe school closures would have specific effects, like not mingling with social contacts and radical change in daily routine.
Furthermore, evidence shows that children and adolescents had less of a loss in social mixing than other age groups during lockdowns. This suggests that the majority of the reduction in social mixing for youth was school closure.


18-60\% of youth scored above thresholds for risk of psychological difficulties (higher than pre-COVID).
50-65\% reductions reported in presentations for self-harm; 40\% reduction in psychiatric admissions.

This plus the increase in psychological distress (and notably the school closures, considering how many children rely on school care) suggests that there were lots of unmet mental health needs during first wave.


Upwards of 1/4 of children may have developed sleeping problems.
Overall, decrease in healthy behaviours (e.g. physical activity) and increase in unhealthy diet and screen time behaviors (latter hard to separate from online learning).
Possibility for long-term sequelae.

Study Limitations

Narrative synthesis rather than a meta-analysis.

Apparently the heterogeneity of the designs and measures was too high to do so.
Narrative synthesis = "grouping studies according to the type of outcome".
Greater qualitative weighing to longitudinal and higher quality studies.


No formal assessment for reporting bias or publication bias.
No studies separated school closures from broader social lockdowns.
Couldn't break down data specifically by age.

