@article{los_effective_2008,
	title = {The effective time course of preparation},
	volume = {57},
	issn = {00100285},
	url = {https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0010028507000692},
	doi = {10.1016/j.cogpsych.2007.11.001},
	abstract = {In reaction time (RT) research on nonspeciﬁc preparation, the preparation period is often identiﬁed with the foreperiod (FP), the interval between the oﬀset of a neutral warning stimulus (S1) and the onset of the reaction stimulus (S2). However, the ‘‘eﬀective preparation period” may be longer than FP: nonspeciﬁc preparation may start prior to FP (e.g., at the onset of S1) and/or continue after it (i.e., in parallel with the reaction process). In four experiments, we factorially varied FP and an additional factor (S1-duration; S2-luminance; stimulus–response compatibility) that probed the eﬀective preparation period outside the bounds of FP. By examining how equivalent RT–FP functions obtain at the diﬀerent levels of the additional factor, we showed that nonspeciﬁc preparation (1) starts at the onset of S1 for brief FPs but at its oﬀset for longer FPs and (2) continues in parallel with S2-encoding but stops prior to response selection.},
	language = {en},
	number = {1},
	urldate = {2022-06-07},
	journal = {Cognitive Psychology},
	author = {Los, Sander A. and Schut, Marcus L.J.},
	month = aug,
	year = {2008},
	pages = {20--55},
	annote = {Focus on: E1, E3, and E4
APA7 Citation:
Los, S.A., \& Schut, M.L.J. (2008). The effective time course of preparation. Cognitive Psychology, 57, 20-55.
Abstract


The “effective preparation period” (i.e., the period in which people prepare their attention) is commonly identified with the “foreperiod” (FP), which is the time between the disappearance of a cue/warning stimulus (S1) and the appearance of a target stimulus (S2).


However, the effective preparation period may actually begin prior to the foreperiod, like as soon as S1 is presented.


In a series of experiments, this study manipulated 2 variables:


Foreperiod (FP): The length of the period between the disappearence of S1 and the appearance of S2.


S1-duration: The amount of time that S1 is present.


S2-luminance: How brightly S2 appears as a target.


Stimulus-response compatibility.




The purpose was to examine the temporal properties of the effective preparation period outside of FP (as it is classically defined).


Result: Nonspecific preparation . . .


Begins at the onset of S1 for brief FPs, but begins at the offset for long FPs.


Continues in parallel with S2-encoding but stops prior to response selection.




Introduction


Experimental psychologists study preparation by giving people a warning cue and then a target to respond to. They analyze preparation in terms of mean reaction time (RT), plotted up against the amount of time between the warning cue/stimulus (S1) and the target stimulus (S2).


Preparation function: Reaction time as a function of either foreperiod (FP; time between S1 offset and S2 onset) or stimulus onset asynchrony (SOA; time between S1 onset and S2 onset).


The preparation function is ambiguous as to whether the effective preparation period begins at the onset or offset of S1, or somewhere in between, and does not demonstrate where the preparation period ends.





Preliminary distinctions and assumptions


Specific vs nonspecific preparation: Specific preparation is enabled when S1 is informative as to the response stimulus, whether it indicates target identity, probability, etc. Nonspecific preparation occurs when S1 is uninformative as to the response stimulus.


Specific preparation is assumed to reduce the computational complexity of response to S2.


Nonspecific preparation is assumed not to reduce the computational complexity of response, but instead merely increases alertness.




The present study focuses on nonspecific preparation, which permits for two main assumptions:


First, an increase in alertness via nonspecific preparation either speeds up computation of the response to S2, or lowers the criterion for activating computation of S2.


Second, nonspecific preparation is noncomputational. Therefore, reaction and preparation are mutually noncontingent – i.e., neither relies on the other to occur. So it is possible to experimentally separate reaction and nonspecific preparation without worrying that they’re computationally overlapping.





The effective preparation period





When does preparation start?


Unclear whether preparation begins at S1-on or S1-off. It could be both, depending on the circumstance.


Hypothesis: Specifically, they hypothesized that preparation would begin at either S1-on or S1-off depending on:


Which marker is a more reliable predictor of the onset of S2.


Which marker appears at an interval that is long enough to allow appropriate preparation, but short enough so that the prepatory state doesn’t dissipate over time.






When does preparation end?


Serial view of preparation: The claim that the effective preparation period ends upon presentation of S2. This view is a logical consequent of the claim that the effective preparation period is the foreperiod.


Alternative parallel view of preparation: Preparation continues after S2, until the process drawing on preparation (process Y in Fig. 1) begins operating on the input delivered by the predecessor process (process X). Therefore, preparation continues until S2 encoding is terminated.


Edited version of Figure 1 to clarify these views:





Theoretical justification for parallel view:


If reaction and preparation are mutually noncontingent, then they ought to be able to co-occur. But the serial view implies that they are mutually contingent, such that reaction can only occur upon the completion of preparation.


The authors believe that the empirical evidence for parallel processing is on their side.










Experimental approach


Hypotheses:


“the effective preparation period starts either at the onset or at the offset of S1, depending on the duration of FP, and lasts at least until S2 encoding has terminated.” (26).




The basic idea of the experiment is this: under what conditions can the same state of effective preparation be activated? If there are multiple sets of conditions under which this preparation period can be activated in the same manner, than those conditions are said to be psychologically equivalent.


The two variables used to define these conditions are:


Foreperiod


Other variables across the four experiments that lengthened effective preparation prior to FP:


Experiments 1 \& 2: S1 duration


Experiments 3 \& 4: S2 luminance and stimulus-response compatibility




If changing the additional variable, G, from G1 to G2 leads to an increase of the effective preparation by D ms, then the prepatory state in condition (G1, FPi) should be equivalent to that in (G2, FPi - D ms).






There were six levels of FP to test for equivalence conditions for RT-FP. Furthermore, the additional variable had two conditions, for a total of 12 (6 x 2) factors.



Experiment 1


Manipulations:


FP: Ranged from 0-250 ms


S1 duration: Either 50 or 150 ms


S1 onset and offset equally reliable predictors for S2 onset.






Prediction: Given that S1 duration and FP are very brief, S1 onset will be a more efficient time marker for S2 onset. Therefore, when the preparation function is written in terms of SOA, the functions will be equivalent for both S1 durations. But they will not be equivalent when written in terms of FP.


Methods


N = 12


Stimuli:


S1 = auditory tone


S2 = white square presented to the left or right of a vertical bar at the center of the screen




Procedure:


S1 presents for either 50 or 150 ms


S1 offset followed by FP of 0, 50, 100, 150, 200, or 250 ms


S2 onset equally probable at left or right position relative to vertical bar


Participants press left or right SHIFT key depending on which side the white box (S2) appears on


After each block (total of 12 blocks across 2 sessions), participants were given their RT and accuracy scores to write down and keep track of their performance.




Results





Fig. 2A: Significant main effect of S1 duration, along with interaction between S1 duration and FP. For S1 duration of 50 ms, participants get faster as FP increases. For S1 duration of 150 ms, participants get slower as FP increases.


Fig. 2B: Marginally significant main effect of S1 duration. Not significant main effect of SOA nor interaction of SOA with S1 duration.


Fig. 2C: Marginally significant interaction between S1 and FP. More errors for FP ≤ 100 ms for S1 = 150 ms.


Fig. 2D: No effects approached significance.




Discussion


When the preparation interval is expressed in terms of SOA, the mean RTs are equivalent (Fig. 2B) whereas they are not when it is expressed in terms of FP (Fig. 2A). The error rates are also more similar when expressed in SOA (Fig. 2D).


Therefore, preparation is triggered by S1-onset when FPs and S1-durations are very brief.





Experiment 2


Manipulations:


Same as Experiment 1, except that they tried a longer S1 duration and some different FPs.


S1 durations: 50 ms \& 650 ms


FPs: ranging frmo 600 to 2100 ms


Unlike in Experiment 1, the shortest FP of 600 ms is considerably longer and therefore past the 250-300 ms preparation interval. So, the offset of S1 should be a more efficient trigger of preparation than onset.




Prediction: The preparation function for the two FPs ought to be equivalent when RT is expressed in terms of FP but not when expressed in terms of SOA.




Results





Fig. 3A: Significant main effect of FP; RT increases as FP increases. Unlike Experiment 1, no significant main effect of S1 duration nor interaction between FP and S1 duration.


Fig. 3B: Significant main effect of SOA. Significant main effect of S1 duration. No significant interaction between SOA and S1 duration.


Fig. 3C \& 3D: No significant effects on error rates.





Discussion


When FPs and S1 durations are relatively long, the preparation functions of both S1 duration conditions are equivalent when expressed as a function of FP but not of SOA.


In the context of relatively long FPs, preparation is triggered by the offset of S1.


Experiments 1 and 2 confirmed the hypothesis that preparation is flexibly triggered by the onset or offset of S1, depending on the length of FPs and S1 durations.


An underadditive-factor method


The first sections of this paper focused on the beginning of the preparation period. Now it will focus on the end.


Additive factor method: “Two factors exhibit additive effects if (1) processes are arranged in stages (i.e., as epochs without temporal overlap), and (2) the factors influence these processes selectively in that they do not influence a common process. If either of these conditions is not met, the factors are likely to exhibit an interaction effect.” (32).


I.e., factors are additive when they don’t occur simultaneously and they don’t affect a common process.


The additive factor method is invalid for a parallel view of preparation, because parallel processing implies a violation of premise 1, that processes are arranged in stages.




Additive factor method applied to preparation: Assume that FP influences process Y, and G influences either X, Y, or Z. Further assume the serial view, such that processes X, Y, and Z (as well as preparation) do not share temporal overlap. 


If G influences either process X or Z but not Y, then FP and G would exhibit additive effects. 


Denial of the consequent implies that FP and G are interactive, and so G influences Y. 




If G influences process Y, then FP and G would probably interact. 


Denial of the consequent implies that G doesn’t influence process Y. 






Underadditive factor method applied to preparation: The serial view makes predictions consistent with the additive factor method, but the parallel view does not because factors can share temporal overlap without interacting. Given that we have reason to believe the parallel view (Experiment 1), we must apply the underadditive method. 


Suppose that X involves encoding, Y involves deciding, and Z involves responding, as the three components of the reaction process. Further assume that preparation occurs parallel to encoding. 







In Fig. 4, A1 and A2, we have an underadditive interaction: G influences some process X, causing it to lengthen. The lengthening of X shortens Y by increasing the supply of preparation. Thus, there is a tradeoff between X and Y, such that an increase in X implies a decrease in Y. This tradeoff effect would is underadditive because it would be bigger for short FPs (cases where the supply of preparation is low and the demand is high; G increases supply, thereby having a smaller overall effect) than for long FPs (cases where the supply of preparation is high and the demand is low; G increases supply, thereby having a larger overall effect by dragging X out further than necessary). 


For the underadditive interaction, we have an especially powerful inferential tool. If G has an effect of D ms on process X, then it will have a twofold effect on the RT-FP function: 


First, by lengthening the serial component (process X) of the reaction process by D ms, it will lift the RT-FP function D ms upward. 


Second, by lengthening the duration of the effective preparation period by D ms, it will shift the RT-FP function D ms to the left. So, we obtain the following equivalence condition: 


Equivalence condition: RT(G1, FPi) = RT(G2, FPi - D) - D
















Experiment 3


Experiment 3 tested the serial and parallel views by using FP and S2 luminance as factors. 


Stimulus luminance influences early encoding processes, according to prior research. 


Preparation influences processes beyond encoding, according to prior research. 


Therefore, if the serial view is true, then the effect relation between FP and S2 should be additive. But if the parallel view is true, it should be an underadditive interaction. 




Method


S2 could be either bright or dim. S1 remained constant both in luminance and in presentation time. 


Results





As seen in Fig. 5A, the interaction is underadditive: the effect of luminance was larger for long FPs than for short FPs. 





Fig. 5A indicates that preparation continues during encoding (X). To test this, they used their equivalence condition: 





They took both S2 bright and dim at their lower bound values (FP{\textgreater}150 ms) and estimated D = 74 ms (the average D at that point onwards). They then shifted the response times of the dim condition accordingly, and plotted their coordinates with the bright condition to see if they correlated – and they did! 


Therefore, you can describe all these data points in terms of FP with an exponential decay function, without invoking S2 luminance – that’s the point of an equivalence condition. Nice. 






Discussion


This experiment showed a strong underadditive interaction between S2 luminance and FP. Therefore, preparation continues unimpeded during S2 encoding (process X). 


Experiment 4


Experiment 1 showed that preparation occurs at S1 onset when S1 and FP are brief, and at S1 offset when FP is long. 


Experiment 3 showed that preparation continues parallel to (during) process X. 


Experiment 4 will test whether preparation continues past process X, into later processes. 


To test preparation in E4, they manipulated stimulus-response compatibility (SRC): 


Compatible condition: Locations of S2 and the correct response key were spatially congruent. 


Incompatible condition: Locations of S2 and the correct response key were spatially incongruent. 




SRC influences the duration of the response-selection process, according to past research. 


This is also a replication of Poster et al (1971; Experiment 1), who found data trending towards an underadditive interaction for SRC, but did not approach significance. 


Method


S2 luminance fixed at bright level instead of varying as in E3. 


SRC was either compatible or incompatible. 





FP and SRC were purely additive, in stark contrast to E3. The equivalence function showed they are, in fact, equivalent – they’re just additive rather than interactive functions. 




Discussion


The effects of FP and SRC on RT combined additively. 


Therefore, preparation continues in parallel with S2-encoding, but stops prior to response selection. 


